summary
    Here's a pro tip: If a publicist emails you and asks if you'd be interested in attending the grand opening of a Hard Rock Hotel in Cancun, all expenses paid, for three days of laying out by the pool, eating more food than Honey Boo Boo's mom at a buffet and generally behaving like a [...]
content
    [{'base': u'http://newsroom.mtv.com/feed/', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<p><img src="http://newsroom.mtv.com//wp-content/uploads/news/2012/10/florida_600.jpg" /></p>\n<p>Here\'s a pro tip: If a publicist emails you and asks if you\'d be interested in attending the grand opening of a <a href="http://www.hardrockhotels.com/cancun.aspx" target="_blank">Hard Rock Hotel in Cancun</a>, all expenses paid, for three days of laying out by the pool, eating more food than Honey Boo Boo\'s mom at a buffet and generally behaving like a Kanye West/Kim Dotcom hybrid \u2026 all sandwiched in-between concerts from Flo Rida and the Goo Goo Dolls, well, then you should most definitely say "<i>Yes</i>."</p>\n<p>Because that\'s what I did. For three days this weekend, I checked my journalistic integrity at the door and partied like a genuine rock star at the sparkly new Hard Rock in Cancun, a 12-story gem that juts out into the Caribbean Sea, features some 600 rooms, five international restaurants, five bars (including two of the "swim-up" variety) and a lobby packed with enough memorabilia to give the Rock Hall pause (checking out John Bonham\'s kit up close was a thrill \u2026 what can I say, I\'m a rock nerd). There were parties and after-parties, booming DJ sets by the pool, white sand beaches, endless Hors d\'oeuvres and at one point, they christened the thing with a guitar-smash, one attended by a little person dressed up like Gene Simmons. Needless to say, one of the better work-cations I\'ve ever been on.</p>\n<p><center><img src="http://newsroom.mtv.com/feed/" /></center></p>\n<p>For the grand opening, the folks at Hard Rock pulled out all the stops, which meant, that, in addition to the fashion show I attended &#8212; I wore a button-up shirt and everything &#8212; there were also two nights of concerts. <a href="http://www.mtv.com/artists/flo-rida/">Flo Rida</a> provided the perfect soundtrack to a very <i>loose</i> first night, ripping through a set of his patented party-starters ("Low," "In The Ayer," "Right Round," etc) and even bringing a bunch of ladies up on stage at one point for an impromptu dance-off. Shoot, he had such a good time that he even stuck around the next day, and was seen by <i>this</i> reporter wading out into the crystal-blue ocean in a pair of gigantic red trunks.</p>\n<p>The <a href="http://www.mtv.com/artists/goo-goo-dolls/">Goo Goo Dolls</a> performed on night two, and served reminder that they possess a back catalog as formidable as, well, <i>anyone,</i> leading a fired-up crowd through rousing sing-alongs on hits like "Name," "Iris," "Black Balloon" and "Slide." And despite forming in Buffalo, New York, they seemed at home on the Hard Rock\'s beach stage, rocking long into the night.</p>\n<p>There were also celebrity cameos by the aforementioned Willis (who, it should be noted, was definitely feeling the Goo Goo Dolls) and Wilmer Valderrama, who hosted a Saturday afternoon pool party from high-atop a DJ booth, staged a "Dougie" competition and posed for about a bazillion photos. Oh, and then I got an "organic facial" from the Hard Rock spa. It definitely helped with the hangover.</p>\n<p>All-in-all, it was a pretty tremendous weekend, and now that I\'m sitting here back in gloomy New York, typing this with my tan slowly peeling away (it\'s seriously gross), I can tell you without a doubt that you should definitely make your way down to the Hard Rock in Cancun sometime \u2026 even <i>if</i> a publicist isn\'t paying your way, it\'s sure to be a trip you won\'t forget. Even if you can\'t remember most of it.</p>', 'language': None}]

summary
    When Snoop Lion appeared on "RapFix Live" in April, he weighed in on the controversy surrounding Rick Ross' lyrics on "U.O.E.N.O." (which would eventually signal the end of Rozay's Reebok deal), stating bluntly, "When you're buying Snoop Dogg you're buying all that comes with it. When you're buying Rozay, you're buying all that comes with [...]
content
    [{'base': u'http://rapfix.mtv.com/feed', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<p><img alt="Radio 1 Big Weekend Festival - Day 1" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-86985" height="381" src="http://rapfix.mtv.com//wp-content/uploads/rapfix/2013/07/jcole.jpg" width="575" /></p>\n<p>When Snoop Lion <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706311/snoop-lion-defends-rick-ross-reebok-freedom-speech.jhtml" target="_blank">appeared on "RapFix Live" </a>in April, he weighed in on the controversy surrounding Rick Ross\' lyrics on "U.O.E.N.O." (which would eventually signal the <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1705463/rick-ross-reebok-controversy.jhtml" target="_blank">end of Rozay\'s Reebok deal</a>), stating bluntly, "When you\'re buying Snoop Dogg you\'re buying all that comes with it. When you\'re buying Rozay, you\'re buying all that comes with it." That sentiment doesn\'t seem to apply in 2013, though, with rappers like Drake and J. Cole issuing full-blown apologies for content that seems PG by rap standards. When all is said and done, are these rappers better off apologizing, or remaining mum?<span id="more-86961"></span></p>\n<p><strong>Rick Ross</strong>: Though Rocko\'s "U.O.E.N.O." had been out for weeks before anyone bothered to take issue with Rozay\'s lyrics, when the drama began it really took off. Protests were held at the Reebok store in NYC and for days fans flooded Ross\' Twitter timeline with hateful messages. At the peak of the uproar, the MMG CEO <a href="http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/03/29/rick-ross-explanation-for-u-o-e-n-o-fuels-rape-lyrics-debate/" target="_blank"><em>attempted</em> to apologize</a>, but he really might\'ve been better off just saying nothing at all. "There was a misunderstanding with a lyric, a misinterpretation," Ross said during a radio interview at the time. "I would never use the term \'rape\' in my records and as far as my camp. Hip-hop don\'t condone that, the streets don\'t condone that, <i>nobody</i> condones that." After this, the slander was only amplified, with fans accusing Ross of trying to get out of a real apology. (Note to self: never use the word "misinterpretation" in an apology).</p>\n<p><strong>Lil Wayne: </strong>Weezy isn\'t the first rapper to reference Emmett Till in a rap song (see: Kanye\'s "Through the Wire") but the manner in which the civil rights figure\'s name was used on "Karate Chop" really struck a chord. The Till estate was so publicly outraged, that Wayne\'s camp <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706687/lil-wayne-emmett-till-apology-family.jhtml" target="_blank">actually issued an apology</a>. Well, something like that. Nowhere in the statement was there really an apology for the lyrics, as much as an apology for the Tills taking offense. Count this as another situation where the attempted apology did more harm than good. Amazingly enough, earlier this month during a show in Tennessee, Wayne <a href="http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/07/15/lil-wayne-apologizes-to-emmett-tills-family-during-concert/" target="_blank">finally issued a verbal \'sorry\'</a> to the Till family--3 months after the controversy. Better late than never? Perhaps.</p>\n<p><strong>Tyler, The Creator</strong>: Although lyrics weren\'t at the center of this particular controversy, we\'d like to point back to Snoop Lion\'s statement in the case of Tyler, The Creator and Mountain Dew. The Odd Future frontman, known for his off-the-wall antics and often offensive lyrics, was forced to defend his silly Mountain Dew ad against claims of racism in May. His management <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706665/tyler-the-creator-mountain-dew-ad-controversy.jhtml" target="_blank">issued a statement</a> noting that "It was never Tyler\'s intention to offend," and Mountain Dew swiftly pulled the ads from both TV and web. Tyler was <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706757/tyler-the-creator-mountain-dew-ad-ridiculous.jhtml" target="_blank">diplomatic enough to listen to Dr. Boyce Watkins outlandish claims</a> (might we go so far as to call it trolling?) and be respectful, while accurately calling the ban "ridiculous." <em>Completely</em> ridiculous. If we could invoke Snoop for a moment: "Dear Mountain Dew, when you\'re buying Tyler, The Creator you\'re buying all that comes with it."</p>\n<p><strong>J. Cole and Drake</strong>: This month autism advocates took aim at J. Cole for some distasteful lyrics on Drake\'s <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1709450/drake-nothing-was-the-same.jhtml">Jodeci Freestyle,</a> and the criticism didn\'t go unnoticed by the Roc Nation rapper, or his OVO counterpart. Cole <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1711030/j-cole-apology-autism.jhtml" target="_blank">issued a sincere apology</a> via his <em>Dreamvillain</em> blog, ("Last week, when I first saw a comment from someone outraged about the lyric, I realized right away that what I said was wrong") and <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1711078/drake-j-cole-autism-jodeci-freestyle.jhtml" target="_blank">Drake followed a day later with his own sorry</a>, adding, "I share responsibility and offer my sincerest apologies for the pain this has caused." Kudos to Drake and Cole for issuing real apologies that couldn\'t be,um, "misinterpreted"...but we\'d like to pose this question: Did it really take a complaint to highlight the fact that the lyrics could be deemed offensive to begin with? Or did a little pressure force an unnecessary apology?</p>\n<p><em>Do you think rappers should continue to apologize when criticized for their work, or does Snoop Lion have the right idea?</em></p>', 'language': None}]

    July 31, 2013 - In this sequel to the hybrid live action/animated family blockbuster comedy The Smurfs, the evil wizard Gargamel creates a couple of mischievous Smurf-like creatures called the Naughties that he hopes will let him harness the all-powerful, magical Smurf-essence. But when he discovers that only a real Smurf can give him what he wants — and only a secret spell that Smurfette knows can turn the Naughties into real Smurfs — Gargamel kidnaps Smurfette and brings her to Paris, where he has been winning the adoration of millions as the world's greatest sorcerer. It's up to Papa, Clumsy, Grouchy, and Vanity to return to our world, reunite with their human friends Patrick and Grace Winslow, and rescue her! Will Smurfette, who has always felt different from the other Smurfs, find a new connection with the Naughties Vexy and Hackus – or will the Smurfs convince her that their love for her is True Blue?<p>Go to FilmJabber.com to see <a href="http://www.filmjabber.com/movie-preview/smurfs-2.html">Smurfs 2 movie information</a>.<img height="1" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/Movies-Coming-Soon-FilmJabber/~4/vwP-dswGmIk" width="1" />

summary
    Here's a pro tip: If a publicist emails you and asks if you'd be interested in attending the grand opening of a Hard Rock Hotel in Cancun, all expenses paid, for three days of laying out by the pool, eating more food than Honey Boo Boo's mom at a buffet and generally behaving like a [...]
content
    [{'base': u'http://newsroom.mtv.com/feed/', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<p><img src="http://newsroom.mtv.com//wp-content/uploads/news/2012/10/florida_600.jpg" /></p>\n<p>Here\'s a pro tip: If a publicist emails you and asks if you\'d be interested in attending the grand opening of a <a href="http://www.hardrockhotels.com/cancun.aspx" target="_blank">Hard Rock Hotel in Cancun</a>, all expenses paid, for three days of laying out by the pool, eating more food than Honey Boo Boo\'s mom at a buffet and generally behaving like a Kanye West/Kim Dotcom hybrid \u2026 all sandwiched in-between concerts from Flo Rida and the Goo Goo Dolls, well, then you should most definitely say "<i>Yes</i>."</p>\n<p>Because that\'s what I did. For three days this weekend, I checked my journalistic integrity at the door and partied like a genuine rock star at the sparkly new Hard Rock in Cancun, a 12-story gem that juts out into the Caribbean Sea, features some 600 rooms, five international restaurants, five bars (including two of the "swim-up" variety) and a lobby packed with enough memorabilia to give the Rock Hall pause (checking out John Bonham\'s kit up close was a thrill \u2026 what can I say, I\'m a rock nerd). There were parties and after-parties, booming DJ sets by the pool, white sand beaches, endless Hors d\'oeuvres and at one point, they christened the thing with a guitar-smash, one attended by a little person dressed up like Gene Simmons. Needless to say, one of the better work-cations I\'ve ever been on.</p>\n<p><center><img src="http://newsroom.mtv.com/feed/" /></center></p>\n<p>For the grand opening, the folks at Hard Rock pulled out all the stops, which meant, that, in addition to the fashion show I attended &#8212; I wore a button-up shirt and everything &#8212; there were also two nights of concerts. <a href="http://www.mtv.com/artists/flo-rida/">Flo Rida</a> provided the perfect soundtrack to a very <i>loose</i> first night, ripping through a set of his patented party-starters ("Low," "In The Ayer," "Right Round," etc) and even bringing a bunch of ladies up on stage at one point for an impromptu dance-off. Shoot, he had such a good time that he even stuck around the next day, and was seen by <i>this</i> reporter wading out into the crystal-blue ocean in a pair of gigantic red trunks.</p>\n<p>The <a href="http://www.mtv.com/artists/goo-goo-dolls/">Goo Goo Dolls</a> performed on night two, and served reminder that they possess a back catalog as formidable as, well, <i>anyone,</i> leading a fired-up crowd through rousing sing-alongs on hits like "Name," "Iris," "Black Balloon" and "Slide." And despite forming in Buffalo, New York, they seemed at home on the Hard Rock\'s beach stage, rocking long into the night.</p>\n<p>There were also celebrity cameos by the aforementioned Willis (who, it should be noted, was definitely feeling the Goo Goo Dolls) and Wilmer Valderrama, who hosted a Saturday afternoon pool party from high-atop a DJ booth, staged a "Dougie" competition and posed for about a bazillion photos. Oh, and then I got an "organic facial" from the Hard Rock spa. It definitely helped with the hangover.</p>\n<p>All-in-all, it was a pretty tremendous weekend, and now that I\'m sitting here back in gloomy New York, typing this with my tan slowly peeling away (it\'s seriously gross), I can tell you without a doubt that you should definitely make your way down to the Hard Rock in Cancun sometime \u2026 even <i>if</i> a publicist isn\'t paying your way, it\'s sure to be a trip you won\'t forget. Even if you can\'t remember most of it.</p>', 'language': None}]

summary
    When Snoop Lion appeared on "RapFix Live" in April, he weighed in on the controversy surrounding Rick Ross' lyrics on "U.O.E.N.O." (which would eventually signal the end of Rozay's Reebok deal), stating bluntly, "When you're buying Snoop Dogg you're buying all that comes with it. When you're buying Rozay, you're buying all that comes with [...]
content
    [{'base': u'http://rapfix.mtv.com/feed', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<p><img alt="Radio 1 Big Weekend Festival - Day 1" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-86985" height="381" src="http://rapfix.mtv.com//wp-content/uploads/rapfix/2013/07/jcole.jpg" width="575" /></p>\n<p>When Snoop Lion <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706311/snoop-lion-defends-rick-ross-reebok-freedom-speech.jhtml" target="_blank">appeared on "RapFix Live" </a>in April, he weighed in on the controversy surrounding Rick Ross\' lyrics on "U.O.E.N.O." (which would eventually signal the <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1705463/rick-ross-reebok-controversy.jhtml" target="_blank">end of Rozay\'s Reebok deal</a>), stating bluntly, "When you\'re buying Snoop Dogg you\'re buying all that comes with it. When you\'re buying Rozay, you\'re buying all that comes with it." That sentiment doesn\'t seem to apply in 2013, though, with rappers like Drake and J. Cole issuing full-blown apologies for content that seems PG by rap standards. When all is said and done, are these rappers better off apologizing, or remaining mum?<span id="more-86961"></span></p>\n<p><strong>Rick Ross</strong>: Though Rocko\'s "U.O.E.N.O." had been out for weeks before anyone bothered to take issue with Rozay\'s lyrics, when the drama began it really took off. Protests were held at the Reebok store in NYC and for days fans flooded Ross\' Twitter timeline with hateful messages. At the peak of the uproar, the MMG CEO <a href="http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/03/29/rick-ross-explanation-for-u-o-e-n-o-fuels-rape-lyrics-debate/" target="_blank"><em>attempted</em> to apologize</a>, but he really might\'ve been better off just saying nothing at all. "There was a misunderstanding with a lyric, a misinterpretation," Ross said during a radio interview at the time. "I would never use the term \'rape\' in my records and as far as my camp. Hip-hop don\'t condone that, the streets don\'t condone that, <i>nobody</i> condones that." After this, the slander was only amplified, with fans accusing Ross of trying to get out of a real apology. (Note to self: never use the word "misinterpretation" in an apology).</p>\n<p><strong>Lil Wayne: </strong>Weezy isn\'t the first rapper to reference Emmett Till in a rap song (see: Kanye\'s "Through the Wire") but the manner in which the civil rights figure\'s name was used on "Karate Chop" really struck a chord. The Till estate was so publicly outraged, that Wayne\'s camp <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706687/lil-wayne-emmett-till-apology-family.jhtml" target="_blank">actually issued an apology</a>. Well, something like that. Nowhere in the statement was there really an apology for the lyrics, as much as an apology for the Tills taking offense. Count this as another situation where the attempted apology did more harm than good. Amazingly enough, earlier this month during a show in Tennessee, Wayne <a href="http://rapfix.mtv.com/2013/07/15/lil-wayne-apologizes-to-emmett-tills-family-during-concert/" target="_blank">finally issued a verbal \'sorry\'</a> to the Till family--3 months after the controversy. Better late than never? Perhaps.</p>\n<p><strong>Tyler, The Creator</strong>: Although lyrics weren\'t at the center of this particular controversy, we\'d like to point back to Snoop Lion\'s statement in the case of Tyler, The Creator and Mountain Dew. The Odd Future frontman, known for his off-the-wall antics and often offensive lyrics, was forced to defend his silly Mountain Dew ad against claims of racism in May. His management <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706665/tyler-the-creator-mountain-dew-ad-controversy.jhtml" target="_blank">issued a statement</a> noting that "It was never Tyler\'s intention to offend," and Mountain Dew swiftly pulled the ads from both TV and web. Tyler was <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1706757/tyler-the-creator-mountain-dew-ad-ridiculous.jhtml" target="_blank">diplomatic enough to listen to Dr. Boyce Watkins outlandish claims</a> (might we go so far as to call it trolling?) and be respectful, while accurately calling the ban "ridiculous." <em>Completely</em> ridiculous. If we could invoke Snoop for a moment: "Dear Mountain Dew, when you\'re buying Tyler, The Creator you\'re buying all that comes with it."</p>\n<p><strong>J. Cole and Drake</strong>: This month autism advocates took aim at J. Cole for some distasteful lyrics on Drake\'s <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1709450/drake-nothing-was-the-same.jhtml">Jodeci Freestyle,</a> and the criticism didn\'t go unnoticed by the Roc Nation rapper, or his OVO counterpart. Cole <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1711030/j-cole-apology-autism.jhtml" target="_blank">issued a sincere apology</a> via his <em>Dreamvillain</em> blog, ("Last week, when I first saw a comment from someone outraged about the lyric, I realized right away that what I said was wrong") and <a href="http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1711078/drake-j-cole-autism-jodeci-freestyle.jhtml" target="_blank">Drake followed a day later with his own sorry</a>, adding, "I share responsibility and offer my sincerest apologies for the pain this has caused." Kudos to Drake and Cole for issuing real apologies that couldn\'t be,um, "misinterpreted"...but we\'d like to pose this question: Did it really take a complaint to highlight the fact that the lyrics could be deemed offensive to begin with? Or did a little pressure force an unnecessary apology?</p>\n<p><em>Do you think rappers should continue to apologize when criticized for their work, or does Snoop Lion have the right idea?</em></p>', 'language': None}]

    [{'base': u'http://feeds.movieweb.com/movieweb_tvnews?format=xml', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<div style="float: right; margin-bottom: 10px;">\n\t<a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/comic-con-2013-schedule-for-thursday-july-18th&amp;service=bit.ly" target="_blank"><img align="right" height="61" src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/comic-con-2013-schedule-for-thursday-july-18th" style="border: none; margin-right: 5px;" width="51" /></a>\n\t\t<a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=http://www.movieweb.com/news/comic-con-2013-schedule-for-thursday-july-18th&amp;src=sp" name="fb_share" style="text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" type="box_count"><img align="right" src="http://media.movieweb.com/i/img/feed/fb.jpg" style="border: none; margin-right: 5px;" /></a>\n\t</div><p>Comic-Con International announced the programming schedule for the first day of San Diego Comic-Con 2013 on Thursday, July 18. You can <a href="http://comiccon2013.sched.org/2013-07-18/list/descriptions/type/1%3A+programs#.UdXEKvn2YrU" target="_blank">clickHere</a> for the full schedule, including comic book-related events, but we have all the movie, DVD, and TV-related panels for you right here. You can also <a class="tv_news_item" href="http://www.movieweb.com/news/warner-bros-reveals-their-tv-lineup-for-comic-con-2013" rel="hc-nekeo7lyynqvom">clickHere</a> to check out the TV pilots that will be presented on Preview Night, Wednesday, July 17. Take a look at what panels and events are happening in San Diego, two weeks from today.</p><p><h2 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.3em;">Thursday, July 18</h2></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">10:00 AM - 11:00 AM <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVLHiRMzC1HlPQ" rel="hc-tvlhirmzc1hlpq">Intelligence</a></h3></p><p>Stars <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/josh-holloway" rel="hc-peqdcxvwmvxyty">Josh Holloway</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVn4jsswZt38qr" rel="hc-tvn4jsswzt38qr">Lost</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/meghan-ory" rel="hc-pe5qza9bcxte8c">Meghan Ory</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVcH59OZuWlFgg" rel="hc-tvch59ozuwlfgg">Once Upon a Time</a>), and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/marg-helgenberger" rel="hc-petetwuckfsfxx">Marg Helgenberger</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVmr1rrsku76pm" rel="hc-tvmr1rrsku76pm">CSI: Crime Scene Investigation</a>) and executive producers <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/michael-seitzman" rel="hc-pe4sv968jub678">Michael Seitzman</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/north-country" rel="hc-fi0nf539378h22">North Country</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/rene-echevarria" rel="hc-perwtxvztfwrvr">Ren&#233 Echevarria</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVC6tLEDF5EyGF" rel="hc-tvc6tledf5eygf">Terra Nova</a>, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVHoSMMPH1ezLO" rel="hc-tvhosmmph1ezlo">Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</a>), and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/tripp-vinson" rel="hc-pevgzevwnovwze">Tripp Vinson</a> discuss the new CBS dramatic thriller. <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/josh-holloway" rel="hc-peqdcxvwmvxyty">Holloway</a> plays Gabriel, a high-tech intelligence operative enhanced with a supercomputer microchip in his brain. With this implant, Gabriel is the first human ever to be connected directly into the worldwide information grid and have complete access to Internet, WiFi, telephone, and satellite data. He can hack into any data center and access key intel in the fight to protect the United States from its enemies. Leading the elite government cybersecurity agency created to support him is Director Lillian Strand (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/marg-helgenberger" rel="hc-petetwuckfsfxx">Helgenberger</a>), a straightforward and efficient boss who oversees the unit\'s missions. Strand assigns Riley Neal (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/meghan-ory" rel="hc-pe5qza9bcxte8c">Ory</a>), a Secret Service agent, to protect Gabriel from outside threats, as well as from his appetite for reckless, unpredictable behavior and disregard for protocol. As the first supercomputer with a beating heart, Gabriel is the most valuable piece of technology the country has ever created and is the U.S.\'s secret weapon. Join the cast and producers for an exclusive viewing of the first episode, followed by a panel discussion moderated by <strong>Debra Birnbaum</strong>, president and editor-in-chief, TV Guide magazine. <strong>Ballroom 20</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">10:15 AM - 11:15 AM <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVanbdagldnFcj" rel="hc-tvanbdagldnfcj">MAD</a> Screening and Q&amp;A</h3></p><p>The <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVanbdagldnFcj" rel="hc-tvanbdagldnfcj">MAD</a>ness continues in San Diego as <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVanbdagldnFcj" rel="hc-tvanbdagldnfcj">MAD</a> once again descends on Comic-Con with their usual-but mostly unusual-brand of hijinks and hilarity. Producers <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/kevin-shinick" rel="hc-pe0ff8170pey31">Kevin Shinick</a> and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/mark-marek" rel="hc-pevt9qanbnntzv">Mark Marek</a> and other hilarious minds from the show promise a wisecracking discussion about the series inspired by the beloved and bestselling humor magazine. Producers will also share new footage featuring all the fan-favorite elements of the show, from animated parodies and crazy commercials to pretend promos and classic gags. This panel is sure to leave everyone feeling <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVanbdagldnFcj" rel="hc-tvanbdagldnfcj">MAD</a>. From Warner Bros. Animation, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVanbdagldnFcj" rel="hc-tvanbdagldnfcj">MAD</a> airs Mondays at 8:30/7:30c on Cartoon Network. <strong>Room 6DE</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">10:30 AM - 11:30 AM 35th <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVnlRsnsmsWUrs" rel="hc-tvnlrsnsmswurs">Battlestar Galactica</a> Celebration</h3></p><p>Host <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/richard-hatch" rel="hc-peohowsqmhg9rr">Richard Hatch</a> (Capt. Apollo, Tom Zarek), director <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/michael-nankin" rel="hc-pedurjddvdaghi">Michael Nankin</a> (<a class="tv_show" (consultant, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVq0LcPYXoGeuu" rel="hc-tvq0lcpyxogeuu">Defiance</a>, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVyYTDDEspdTDy" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/con-air" rel="hc-fitouxyxtfgbwc">Con Air</a>) invite you to get a first look at the futuristic epic romance tale, Star-Crossed. When an spacecraft crash-landed in Emery\'s (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/aimee-teegarden" rel="hc-peizljlpci5ymq">Teegarden</a>) small town when she was only 6, whether the aliens came in peace or with more sinister intentions didn\'t matter: a fierce battle erupted as humans fought for control over their new rivals, an alien species called the Atrians. In the midst of the conflict, Roman (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/matt-lanter" rel="hc-pe3pe878nfbb65">Lanter</a>), a 6-year-old Atrian boy, found his way to a shed behind Emery\'s house, where she protected him from harm. In their brief time together, Emery and Roman forged a deep bond, but the authorities wasted no time tracking Roman down and capturing him. Emery has grown up believing that Roman was killed that day. Ten years later, in 2024, the Atrians have been acclimated to life on Earth, but they are interred in a heavily guarded camp known as the Sector to keep them separate from humans. Now, for the first time, a group of Atrian teens will enroll in a suburban human high school, with the goal of testing the feasibility of human/alien integration. The eyes of the nation and the whole world are fixed on this historical social experiment, an endeavor fraught with suspicion and fear. In the mayhem of the first day, Emery is amazed to learn that Roman was not killed by the authorities and is, in fact, one of the Atrian students. Their childhood bond is quickly rekindled. In a school and a society that distrusts everything about the Atrians, Emery and Roman have found each other again. However, their relationship is threatened by the small-mindedness of their respective communities and the political agendas of people in power. While the world around them rages with anger and prejudice, their bond becomes increasingly strong and increasingly dangerous. As an epic Romeo and Juliet romance unfolds, a violent encounter between their two families could threaten their relationship. Can Roman and Emery\'s love-and peace between the species-survive? The cast and producers offer an exclusive first look at the series, followed by a panel discussion. <strong>Ballroom 20</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">11:45 AM - 12:45 PM DreamWorks Animation Filmmaker Focus</h3></p><p>Join chief creative officer <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/bill-damaschke" rel="hc-pe1jo65ad73f33">Bill Damaschke</a> and directors <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/david-soren" rel="hc-pehkdmlkledwkk">David Soren</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/turbo" rel="hc-fijhd8tdzwbwmq">Turbo</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/rob-minkoff" rel="hc-peou0tounf9nrt">Rob Minkoff</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/mr-peabody-and-sherman" rel="hc-fiewtfiahlspig">Mr. Peabody and Sherman</a>), and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/dean-deblois" rel="hc-pe4fz949ddpu76">Dean DeBlois</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/how-to-train-your-dragon-2" rel="hc-fiitejmqmxbmmn">How to Train Your Dragon 2</a>) as they discuss putting a great story through the animation process and onto the screen. Hilarious hijinks are highly likely to ensue. <strong>Ballroom 20</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">1:10 PM - 2:20 PM <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/europa-report" rel="hc-fij2rby0zws1mq">Europa Report</a></h3></p><p>At the movies, it seems there\'s so much science fiction, but so little science. <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sebastian-cordero" rel="hc-pe2mr839fb2v4b">Sebasti&#225n Cordero</a>\'s <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/europa-report" rel="hc-fij2rby0zws1mq">Europa Report</a> seeks to change that. The film depicts a near-future crewed mission to Jupiter\'s moon Europa, seeking evidence for life in an ocean beneath the moon\'s icy surface. The movie uses current science to tell a story of discovery and danger. This panel features the film\'s crew and cast, alongside scientists involved with a NASA concept for a real robotic spacecraft, the Europa Clipper, designed to investigate the mysteries of Europa, including whether it has the elements to support life. Participants include <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sebastian-cordero" rel="hc-pe2mr839fb2v4b">Sebasti&#225n Cordero</a> (director, <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/rage-2011" rel="hc-fimznus28qonqn">Rage</a> and <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/cronicas" rel="hc-finecoqpsgn1qs">Cronicas</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/bear-mccreary" rel="hc-peiowpjizggllr">Bear McCreary</a> (composer, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVyYTDDEspdTDy" rel="hc-tvyytddespdtdy">Battlestar Galactica</a>, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVhRXkhqQE3nlj" rel="hc-tvhrxkhqqe3nlj">The Walking Dead</a>), producer <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/ben-browning" rel="hc-peoclrqp3bgirq">Ben Browning</a>, and actress <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/karolina-wydra" rel="hc-pe3wpa88sl5z6a">Karolina Wydra</a>, alongside JPL scientists <strong>Steve Vance</strong> and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/kevin-hand" rel="hc-pecurigeh4r7gg">Kevin Hand</a>. Curtis</strong> (set visits), <strong>Rebecca Perry</strong> and <strong>Alex</strong> and <strong>Kellie Rice</strong> (Happy Hobbit), and additional staff dish the latest by and for fans of <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jrr-tolkien" rel="hc-pefi9kfitguqil">J.R.R. Tolkien</a>. <strong>Room 6A</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">6:00 PM - 7:00 PM <a class="tv_season" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVexDMeke5XAhn/season-2" rel="hc-tsclmoexrvsjgg">Mortal Kombat: Legacy Season 2</a> Panel</h3></p><p><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/casper-van-dien" rel="hc-pecqlcciekajff">Casper Van Dien</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/starship-troopers" rel="hc-fiyotbbcw6kscc">Starship Troopers</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/brian-tee" rel="hc-pewr9bwazvynaf">Brian Tee</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-wolverine" rel="hc-fiqyeusude7htv">The Wolverine</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/ian-anthony-dale" rel="hc-peisynnomujqnk">Ian Anthony Dale</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVexDMeke5XAhn" rel="hc-tvexdmeke5xahn">Mortal Kombat: Legacy</a>), <strong>Samantha Jo</strong> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVexDMeke5XAhn" rel="hc-tvexdmeke5xahn">Mortal Kombat: Legacy</a>), and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/ed-boon" rel="hc-pegvtmhm21zxkl">Ed Boon</a> (creator of Mortal Kombat) join series creator and director <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/kevin-tancharoen" rel="hc-peooetovrswmtq">Kevin Tancharoen</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVexDMeke5XAhn" rel="hc-tvexdmeke5xahn">Mortal Kombat: Legacy</a>), producer Lance Sloane (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVexDMeke5XAhn" rel="hc-tvexdmeke5xahn">Mortal Kombat: Legacy</a>/Act of Valor), and Machinima\'s executive vice president of network programming Aaron DeBevoise for an in-depth discussion about the highly anticipated second season of <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVexDMeke5XAhn" rel="hc-tvexdmeke5xahn">Mortal Kombat: Legacy</a>, set to premiere exclusively on Machinima, the number one global video entertainment brand for young males. Moderated by <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/matt-atchity" rel="hc-pe2jibqzapeo59">Matt Atchity</a>, editor-in-chief of Rotten Tomatoes.com, don\'t miss your chance to see exclusive, never-before-seen footage and hear from cast members about the second season of the groundbreaking show that has been called one of the most successful web series of all time. <strong>Indigo Ballroom, Hilton Bayfront</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">6:00 PM - 7:00 PM <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVEbSHIF3V6dIG" rel="hc-tvebshif3v6dig">Teen Wolf</a></h3></p><p>Join cast members <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/tyler-posey" rel="hc-peox4qprw0marv">Tyler Posey</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/crystal-reed" rel="hc-pepawsusghakss">Crystal Reed</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/dylan-obrien-2" rel="hc-pehedcphy3mckq">Dylan O\'Brien</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/tyler-hoechlin" rel="hc-pekralpklwqlnt">Tyler Hoechlin</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/holland-roden" rel="hc-peykrhzerk72ca">Holland Roden</a>, <strong>Charlie Carver</strong>, and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/max-carver" rel="hc-pemr1nnoi1zvqo">Max Carver</a> plus executive producer <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jeff-davis-3" rel="hc-pekmhommasjnos">Jeff Davis</a> for a Q&amp;A as they discuss season 3 and share a special video presentation exclusively for Comic-Con fans. Moderated by ETOnline reporter <strong>Jarett Wieselman</strong>. <strong>Ballroom 20</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">6:00 PM - 7:00 PM <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-goon" rel="hc-fia20fecudejdj">The Goon</a> Kickstarter and Beyond with <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/eric-powell" rel="hc-pekxrpmng4ynnr">Eric Powell</a> and Blur Studios</h3></p><p>Back in November, legions of fans rallied together to raise over $400,000 to put together a story reel for the <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/david-fincher" rel="hc-pezyrgdihrojdg">David Fincher</a>-produced feature film based on <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/eric-powell" rel="hc-pekxrpmng4ynnr">Eric Powell</a>\'s hit comic book series <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-goon" rel="hc-fia20fecudejdj">The Goon</a>! Now, Kickstarter supporters and Comic-Con attendees alike will have a chance to catch an exclusive glimpse of this work in progress! Creator <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/eric-powell" rel="hc-pekxrpmng4ynnr">Eric Powell</a>, Blur Studios owner <strong>Tim Miller</strong>, and veteran visual effects guru <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jeff-fowler" rel="hc-peccrgfhviyhfl">Jeff Fowler</a> present an update on this crowdfunded full-length motion picture. <strong>Room 9</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">6:00 PM - 7:00 PM Adult Swim: <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVJUalwAMCNTOJ" rel="hc-tvjualwamcntoj">The Heart, She Holler</a></h3></p><p>The creators and stars of Adult Swim\'s epic TV event <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVJUalwAMCNTOJ" rel="hc-tvjualwamcntoj">The Heart, She Holler</a> explain it all at this panel. Executive producers <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/john-lee-2" rel="hc-pebqvgdb0vd4fd">John Lee</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVb6dhbhy3r9dh" rel="hc-tvb6dhbhy3r9dh">Xavier: Renegade Angel</a>, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVNkvTNQoVDZSR" rel="hc-tvnkvtnqovdzsr">Wonder Showzen</a>) and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/alyson-levy" rel="hc-pecikhhji912ej">Alyson Levy</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVb6dhbhy3r9dh" rel="hc-tvb6dhbhy3r9dh">Xavier: Renegade Angel</a>, <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVNkvTNQoVDZSR" rel="hc-tvnkvtnqovdzsr">Wonder Showzen</a>) will be joined by cast members <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/patton-oswalt" rel="hc-peghqolkjrueko">Patton Oswalt</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVaZUgafG1mgdg" rel="hc-tvazugafg1mgdg">United States of Tara</a>, <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/ratatouille" rel="hc-ficlwfeg7tqwfd">Ratatouille</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/amy-sedaris" rel="hc-pe53t675nqv778">Amy Sedaris</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVg3umglk9QGjk" rel="hc-tvg3umglk9qgjk">Strangers with Candy</a>), and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/heather-lawless" rel="hc-peskdzxxeydmwt">Heather Lawless</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-campaign" rel="hc-fidx5hkbpytygi">The Campaign</a>).<strong>Room 25ABC</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">6:30 PM - 7:30 PM Showtime: <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5nJb58dTE787" rel="hc-tv5njb58dte787">Dexter</a></h3></p><p>You\'ve been there for every edge of your seat moment, inside <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5nJb58dTE787" rel="hc-tv5njb58dte787">Dexter</a>\'s most intimate thoughts, watching him transform before your eyes. Now, after eight amazing seasons, it\'s time to say goodbye. Join the cast, writers/executive producers and surprise guest stars, who are too big to mention, for a final Comic-Con farewell panel that even Hall H can\'t contain! KROQ entertainment reporter <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/ralph-garman" rel="hc-pejpxolp2q92mj">Ralph Garman</a> presides over a revealing interview and Q&amp;A session with the stars and executive producers of <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5nJb58dTE787" rel="hc-tv5njb58dte787">Dexter</a>. Featured panelists include, but are not limited to series star and executive producer <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/michael-c-hall" rel="hc-pefs6oijk4okho">Michael C. Hall</a>, and series stars <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jennifer-carpenter" rel="hc-pe8yq99cedwqc8">Jennifer Carpenter</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/david-zayas" rel="hc-pe9aegdfuf7ucb">David Zayas</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/james-remar" rel="hc-pelyrultkraeql">James Remar</a>, and special guest star <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/yvonne-strahovski" rel="hc-perlszvzrrs3vr">Yvonne Strahovski</a>. Satisfy your <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5nJb58dTE787" rel="hc-tv5njb58dte787">Dexter</a> obsession all weekend. The new season of <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5nJb58dTE787" rel="hc-tv5njb58dte787">Dexter</a> airs Sundays at 9:00 ET/PT only on Showtime. <strong>Hall H</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">6:45 PM - 7:45 PM <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5adblFemPx88" rel="hc-tv5adblfempx88">Hannibal</a> Feed Your Fears</h3></p><p>Emmy Award-winning executive producer <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/bryan-fuller" rel="hc-pe4mac483kdw6d">Bryan Fuller</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV9vqf9eVpQrcg" rel="hc-tv9vqf9evpqrcg">Pushing Daisies</a>), director <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/david-slade" rel="hc-pewrzcye8ga9zf">David Slade</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-twilight-saga-eclipse" rel="hc-fiolrssvslvbsp">The Twilight Saga: Eclipse</a>), <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/martha-de-laurentiis" rel="hc-petamxuyz7rkwz">Martha De Laurentiis</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/red-dragon" rel="hc-fifzjljnhorwkk">Red Dragon</a>), and star <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/hugh-dancy" rel="hc-peww8cwafosvax">Hugh Dancy</a> (Agent Will Graham) reveal juicy morsels from behind the scenes of the groundbreaking NBC drama <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV5adblFemPx88" rel="hc-tv5adblfempx88">Hannibal</a>. This feast of many courses will serve key moments from the first season as an entree, followed by a digestif of sneak previews of the second season. Not to mention a few surprises along the way. Bon appetit, Fannibals! <strong>Room 6A</strong></div></p><p><div class="box"><h3 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.2em;">8:30 PM - 9:30 PM <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV1Ldnuf1LKJ49" rel="hc-tv1ldnuf1lkj49">Holliston</a>: Inside the Laughs, Screams, Metal, and Geekery!</h3></p><p>Creator/star <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/adam-green" rel="hc-peuhdbvubws3yw">Adam Green</a> (<a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/hatchet" rel="hc-fimeumrmgvs1pr">Hatchet</a>), cast members <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/laura-ortiz" rel="hc-peehdkhnh8yjhj">Laura Ortiz</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVm7ZmmojzGbpt" rel="hc-tvm7zmmojzgbpt">Happy Endings</a>), and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/oderus-urungus" rel="hc-peywedacl1xbca">Oderus Urungus</a> (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/gwar" rel="hc-pegh2llojbhskk">Gwar</a>), director <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sean-becker-2" rel="hc-pej7baiy7wwonk">Sean Becker</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVh6i2A5qJn6jq" rel="hc-tvh6i2a5qjn6jq">The Guild</a>), and fan-favorite moderator <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/alison-haislip" rel="hc-pedtqlfhyfllhl">Alison Haislip</a> (<a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVzEvaLm3Z3MDA" rel="hc-tvzevalm3z3mda">The Voice</a>) discuss the inner workings of their hit television series (now in its second season) and explain the process of creating a sitcom specifically for horror, sci-fi, comic, and heavy metal fans. Including exclusive clips and the world premiere of series character "Lance Rockett" (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/dee-snider" rel="hc-penmpprnxiubrq">Dee Snider</a>, Twisted Sister) and his band Dyver Down\'s first original music video from the upcoming <a class="tv_season" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV1Ldnuf1LKJ49/season-2" rel="hc-tsbtdpc6lsggfc">Season 2</a> finale, this just might be the most you\'ll laugh all weekend long. Q&amp;A to follow the presentation. <strong>Room 24ABC</strong></div></p>\n<div class="feedflare">\n<a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:D7DqB2pKExk"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?i=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:D7DqB2pKExk" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:yIl2AUoC8zA"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?d=yIl2AUoC8zA" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:qj6IDK7rITs"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?d=qj6IDK7rITs" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:I9og5sOYxJI"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?d=I9og5sOYxJI" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?i=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:V_sGLiPBpWU" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:gIN9vFwOqvQ"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?i=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:gIN9vFwOqvQ" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?a=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:F7zBnMyn0Lo"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/movieweb_tvnews?i=WVKniNWzdCc:B1VqcQPHxKA:F7zBnMyn0Lo" /></a>\n</div><img height="1" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/movieweb_tvnews/~4/WVKniNWzdCc" width="1" />', 'language': None}]

An anonymous source feeding new information on the long-unsolved murders to a local reporter (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/juliette-binoche" rel="hc-penzkoruhwwbsp">Juliette Binoche</a>) leads to evidence suggesting a possible cover-up by the former lead detective (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/al-pacino" rel="hc-pentcppvntthrq">Al Pacino</a>) who was on the investigation. As Jonathan digs deeper into the assignment, a dark secret about the case emerges, which threatens to destroy his life and his family.</p><p><a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-son-of-no-one" title="The Son of No One">The Son of No One</a> was released <a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movies/2013/week/2011/week/44" title="November 4th, 2011">November 4th, 2011</a> and stars <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/al-pacino">Al Pacino</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/channing-tatum">Channing Tatum</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/james-ransone">James Ransone</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/ray-liotta">Ray Liotta</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/katie-holmes">Katie Holmes</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/ursula-parker">Ursula Parker</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/brian-gilbert-2">Brian Gilbert</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/tracy-morgan">Tracy Morgan</a>. summary
    A broke medical student turns a profit in the world of underground surgeries in this bloody body modification thriller, in theaters Friday. [...]
content
    [{'base': u'http://feeds.movieweb.com/celebrity-interviews?format=xml', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<div style="float: right; margin-bottom: 10px;">\n\t<a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-jen-and-sylvia-soska-aka-the-twisted-twins-talk-american-mary&amp;service=bit.ly" target="_blank"><img align="right" height="61" src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-jen-and-sylvia-soska-aka-the-twisted-twins-talk-american-mary" style="border: none; margin-right: 5px;" width="51" /></a>\n\t\t<a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-jen-and-sylvia-soska-aka-the-twisted-twins-talk-american-mary&amp;src=sp" name="fb_share" style="text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" type="box_count"><img align="right" src="http://media.movieweb.com/i/img/feed/fb.jpg" style="border: none; margin-right: 5px;" /></a>\n\t</div><p><p><a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary/PGmBhtMisYfspv/7MG9c8e90yvf6df"><img alt="The Twisted Twins Talk American Mary" height="300" src="http://wpc.556e.edgecastcdn.net/80556E/img.site/PHxAFrTmamIGBz_1_m.jpg" title="The Twisted Twins Talk American Mary" width="450" /></a></p></p><p><div align="center"><h4 style="display: block; padding: 10px; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; text-align: center; font-size: 1.1em;">Jen and Sylvia Soska, the Twisted Twins, talk American Mary, in theaters this Friday</h4></div></p><p><a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/dead-hooker-in-a-trunk" rel="hc-fiempiig5hjoii">Dead Hooker in a Trunk</a> duo <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a> and <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a>, otherwise known as The Twisted Twins, are literally changing the face of horror this Friday as their heralded horror neo-classic <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" rel="hc-fi6c0fxkki9j9c">American Mary</a> makes its way to select American theaters.</p><p>This gruesome story follows medical student Mary (<a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/katharine-isabelle" rel="hc-pegjfglhkbvmkm">Katharine Isabelle</a>) who is growing increasingly broke and disenchanted with school and the established doctors she once idolized. The allure of easy money sends her on a desperate quest through the messy world of underground surgeries, which leaves more marks on her than her so-called freakish clientele. As the Twisted Twins will tell you...Appearances are everything.</p><p>We recently caught up with the Canadian duo, who are far less scary than their on-creen cameo appearance in <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" rel="hc-fi6c0fxkki9j9c">American Mary</a> might lead you to believe. Here is our conversation, where we delve into the history behind these characters, some of the true facts about the body modification culture that the movie devotes itself too, and how the pair function as a team.</p><p>Is what we see on screen in <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" rel="hc-fi6c0fxkki9j9c">American Mary</a> real? The Twisted Twins will never tell!</p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: I know this can be a nightmare when we are sitting across from you. When I listen back to some of our audio interviews, I can\'t even tell who\'s who. And I am me!</p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: The confusion doesn\'t bother us at all. A lot of people just call us the twins. That\'s just how it goes. We really are one entity in two different bodies that are identical. There is no offense in it.</p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: Also, if you are an astute studier of our interviews, we also interchange who answers what question. But we will say it verbatim in the exact same way.</p><p><strong>That\'s kind of awesome, though. I like that.</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: Yes, we are actually one functioning human being in two bodies.</p><p><strong>On that note, what is the dynamic like between you two as directors on set? Do you each have your own separate responsibilities? Or do you work together, and interchange those responsibilities?</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: Definitely. Though...Even though we are identical twins, we have very different personalities. On set, we always joke that she\'s the mom and I\'m the dad. She is so giving, she is so there, she knows every little detail down to the tiniest nuance. If I glance over, I\'ll decide if you did something really awesome or really terrible. I get so involved with the world the story is taking place in, the reality within that doesn\'t become fake to me. So <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen</a> has to break that open. She says, "Well, her name is actually <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/katharine-isabelle" rel="hc-pegjfglhkbvmkm">Katie</a>, its not Mary, and you will eventually have to stop talking to her like that.</p><p><strong>I\'d read a couple of articles about the movie before viewing it, and the one thing I kept seeing over and over again is how original American Mary is, and how unique it is in the horror genre. One of the things I noticed is that this may be the first movie in the horror genre that deals with surgery, where someone doesn\'t swing a big sloppy Whopper Jr. over a corpse, munching away as they inspect the body.</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: (Laughs) This is such a weird, fantastical story, we wanted to make sure we kept one foot in reality. I feel bad for all my medical practitioner friends. I had them read the script. I had to make sure that things were realistic. And a lot of these people were not big into body modification. They don\'t believe in those procedures, so we had a flesh artist come on board. He plays the splayed penis guy in the film. He was there to make sure we didn\'t go too out there. This is one of the first films that really deals with body modification. We didn\'t want to do any disrespect to that. We wanted to show these people as they are. The psychotic parts are the things that happen between Mary and her mentor.</p><p><strong>How legal are some of the bodymods that we see in the film?</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: Unfortunatly, if you are going to do body modification...Its funny. If you are going to school, and you want to do body modification, they won\'t let you go if they find out. If you want to be a cosmetic surgeon, not a problem. If you want to practice body modification in North America, as well as other places in the world, you are not allowed to use any anesthetic. I\'m not sure which procedures you are familiar with, but there are some procedures that are extremely painful. The use of anesthetic is vital in order to not make the patient suffer. But there is a slogan that goes along with the bodymod culture, "Some pain is inevitable, but the suffering is optional." You see that a lot with the suspensions that they do as well. They say that the pain is there to remind you that you are alive. I don\'t say there are pain junkets. In life, you come up against pain regardless. You just have a much more intelligent and mature way of coping with pain, and in a way, it\'s a bit of foreplay to cope with the pain. Right now, a lot of people offer body modifications that aren\'t professional. They don\'t use anesthetics. But the thing about the ones that aren\'t professional is, the people that get these modification have to end up going to get them repaired. You can get a lot of money doing modifications. But you see botched jobs. That\'s why we had a consultant on <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" rel="hc-fi6c0fxkki9j9c">American Mary</a>. There is a lot of bad work done on a lot of young people. They so badly want to get it done. But you know, there isn\'t in the Yellow Pages, "Get you tongue forked here."</p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: A lot of these procedures will happen in hotel rooms. They will happen in the back rooms of a tattooing and piercing parlor. I\'ve even heard that they take place in veterinary clinics. There was this one famous case that happened in Alberta. This guy went to see one of these flesh artists to get his penis modified. He brought his friend along with him. Everything went fine. He went home, and everybody was happy. But the friend goes to his parents and tells them what happened. The parents go to the police, and the police go to the flesh artist\'s house. They go through all of his stuff, and all of his books, and they see all of the procedures he has done. And he gets arrested. We don\'t live in a day and age where it\'s safe or expected for people to get these procedures. Whereas, if you want to go into plastic surgery, and you want to get boobs that are three times the size of your head, that\'s totally fine. But if you want to fork your penis or your tongue, that\'s still a little taboo...Well, more than a little bit...</p><p><strong>We do see that scene with the guy and his splayed penis in the movie. In terms of the bodymod culture, what is the craziest thing you saw done to someone\'s penis? What is the most out there procedure?</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: I think voluntary castration would be the thing considered the strangest. I\'m not an owner or operator of a penis. I\'m not sure what the meaning or the thought behind ultimate castration is. To each their own. Maybe they don\'t identify with gender. Or, the ultimate thrill is to film it and have it removed. I think the most shocking thing is double-sized penises, or any amputation, or slicing and forking the member.</p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: Even with castration, a lot of the guys that do these procedures...Someone doesn\'t just call them up and say, "I want my nipples removed today." They do a lot of explaining, making sure these people know what they want to do, and that they are sound minded. One of the things I\'ve seen that is most shocking is called Bagel Head, where they inject saline into your face and around your anatomy, so that makes the flesh pop up and go in this weird circular form. I like the aesthetic of body modification. I like the asymmetry, more than the wackier things. But to each their own. As long as they are able to do it in a safe way. And there is a good reason behind it. A sound minded reason. I can\'t say I have anything against it.</p><p><strong>It certainly sounds like you guys had a lot of material to work with in creating some of the scenes in your screenplay. I don\'t want to give away spoilers, but when you are working towards the end of your film, and what you are setting up as the story is told, how do you decided to reach the conclusion you do knowing someone, somewhere, might want a sequel in this franchise-hungry business that is movies today?</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: I really don\'t like sequels. I have always hated them. I don\'t like that you have this original idea. You are having this discussion about the idea, and then all of a sudden it becomes a money making scheme...Let\'s make this more shocking, cause know you have to connect with the fanbase from the first film. All of the ideas and the heart being watered down over and over again...One of the things I liked about creating a character like Mary was, she was unlike what you usually see. She has flaws. Lots of flaws. To have a character with the freedom to do things like that, there has to be a certain response to that. There are only so many places she can go. Before the end sequence, what ultimately happens with the character, its almost like she is already there. You just see this person go through the roof. She is so naive, and so hopeful about what she wants to do. The pursuit of the American dream, and she takes every chance. But every experience that she has, it just gets ripped away from her, and it gets worse and worse...That\'s a bit of a commentary on the recession and the world we live in right now. The struggles for women in a male dominated industry. It\'s so hard to make ends meet, even now. Think about starting when you are completely impoverished. You want to do great things that cost a lot of money. Well, you will have to make sacrifices. They are going to be amoral sacrifices. The person that you are...Depending on the choices that you make, you may not be the same person you started out as.</p><p><strong>And in regards to Mary herself, this is one of the few females in horror who isn\'t being chased by a killer. And maybe one of the few independent females in any film who could certainly get a boyfriend if she wanted one, but none of her destiny is hinged on a romance of any kind. She is a self-contained, independent woman...</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: It was so important for us to make her that way. Because you see the opposite so often. You see the girl that cries in the shower, you see the girl that runs to her boyfriend, you see the girl that relies on guys to help her out. Just because, how many times have they made women vulnerable? So, yeah. Vulnerability is a part of women, I don\'t know if it\'s a part of men...But for every time they made women a little more forgivable, and more vulnerable, and more sympathetic, you need to have a character that isn\'t. We\'re not all just cookie cutter people. There is darkness in everyone. And some of us never rely on any one. Some of us stand on our own two feet. You see that predominantly with male characters. You want a female character that little girls can look up to.</p><p><strong>Playing off that, can you give me some of the background into the creation of Lance, and how he plays into that in the story, and what he essentially means to the overall arc of the story itself? We don\'t usually get to see the goon, or the muscle, get that moment of humanization. He\'s not just a bodyguard. He\'s a real guy, with real emotion...</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: Thank you so much for saying that, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/twan-holliday" rel="hc-penmnvsvjhfpsn">Twan Holliday</a>, who is playing Lance, really is that character. He is a 7-foot tough guy with all these tattoos that has a heart of gold. The tagline we used for the film, everywhere we could, was that appearances are everything. What does a girl like Mary have in common with someone like Lance? Who is somebody in the bodymod community. Before anyone takes the trouble to get to know you, they judge you on your appearance. What if we changed all of that, and flipped it on its head? We barely see him talking. He is scary, when you see him, the whole time. Then all of a sudden you have the heart of the film, and its exposed. These people are having a conversation without having a conversation. They are talking about the first time they found something really horrible. The justifications, the time, there is a lot of humanity there. I love bringing humanity and real life into characters you don\'t normally see. It was great to have <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/twan-holliday" rel="hc-penmnvsvjhfpsn">Twan Holliday</a> come in as that character. Everytime <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/twan-holliday" rel="hc-penmnvsvjhfpsn">Twan</a> is cast in something, he is a killer. Or he is a thug. You don\'t get this type of opportunity with that kind of aesthetic. I thought, "Wouldn\'t it be nice if we did something different like that?" Especially where you didn\'t expect it. I have read some harsh criticisms. Like, "The twins hate men." No, no, no! I wanted to look at all of these flawed characters. Lance is so sweet and so kind. He may be taking these people, and putting bags over their heads, and making them disappear, but he has that really heartfelt talk, where you have your life out of control, and you don\'t know what your doing, and then all of a sudden somebody is relating to one of these experiences...Then things are starting to make sense again.</p><p><strong>I don\'t want you guys to give away your secrets, but watching the actors in this movie, I never once thought about make-up, or whether I was watching SFX. I never questioned anything, to me it was all-real. I don\'t know if you want to talk about how much of it is make-up, like with Beatrice. I didn\'t look that actress up. I don\'t know if that is her real face, or if its something that was created in a trailer every morning before heading out on set...</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: I won\'t say any spoilers. But that was our entire intention with the film. Not only did we have amazing prosthetics done by MastersFX, who have done <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVr65xrtyFOruA" rel="hc-tvr65xrtyforua">True Blood</a> and <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TVz1OFzzF6ZxDE" rel="hc-tvz1ofzzf6zxde">Six Feet Under</a>. Anytime you\'ve gone, "Oh, my god, that was so cool!" In a film, that has been MastersFX. We also got an actual nod from the community, so that you\'d never know if you were looking at something real or something that was a modification. We grew up in the 80s. That was a time when so many phenomenal artists were doing all of these amazing practical effects. Like <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/jacobs-ladder" rel="hc-fi4upc9dzcjn7b">Jacob\'s Ladder</a> and <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-thing" rel="hc-fi5aa55azc1f79">The Thing</a>. You didn\'t know if it was real. It looks real. There is none of this CGI stuff that takes you out of the moment. I think that is a huge part of how we approach effects in film. Our love for original horror, the stuff that got us really excited. Even though you look at it, and it looks kind of strange, it looks real. Because it was an actual thing. Some CGI is more expensive. Sometimes, people think expensive means better. But anytime I see CGI in a film, and maybe there is a great CGI horror film that blows away my expectations, I can still tell its CGI. It takes me out of the film. It ruins that moment. It destroys that suspension of belief when you are watching a film. There are so many films that do CGI, but some still do practical effects...There is a war going on. They advertised very much that the new <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/evil-dead" rel="hc-fik7lpnpmpnoos">Evil Dead</a> was 100% practical effects. Well, that was a lie. It wasn\'t 100% practical effects. I think that was a misdirect for the fans. On <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" rel="hc-fi6c0fxkki9j9c">American Mary</a>, I can tell you, it was 100% practical effects or real live people.</p><p><strong>I think having 100% practical effects here makes the movie timeless. Especially compared to some of the stuff that comes out now, which looks dated the minute it hits movie screens.</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: I think that\'s absolutely right. Even though I love <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV9WFf9afm1Vcd" rel="hc-tv9wff9afm1vcd">Buffy the Vampire Slayer</a>, anything that was CGI, I watch it now, and I\'m like, "Ahhh...I wish they would have tried that practically." But I will still look at it and think, "Wow, that demon is cool looking."</p><p><strong>You play two twins seeking a special bodymod in the film. We see what that modification is in a drawing, but we never see the two twins live and in the flesh as these two demon girls. What brought that decision, to keep their altered forms a mystery?</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska" rel="hc-pero6uvsulacuu">Sylvia Soska</a></strong>: I would have loved to do that. There was going to be a scene at the end of the movie where Mary is updating her website, that the Twins bought for her, and it was going to have a whole slew of all these different great effects. Everything that she\'d done. We would have gotten to see all of her procedures. Unfortunately, we had 15 days to shoot and a very modest budget. I can\'t speak highly enough of the team that came together, and made this movie under such constraints. But there is so much more I would have liked to say. Its tough. It\'s hard to make a movie that you are emotionally invested in, like we did with <a class="movie" href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" rel="hc-fi6c0fxkki9j9c">American Mary</a>. I sometimes go off at night thinking about this, or thinking about that. It becomes a part of your life. I wanted people to see these things afterwards. And we did go over the designs with MastersFX, with what they were going to look like when the Demon Twins actually became Demon Twins. We never got to look back at that. That is something I\'ve heard from a lot of people, "Well, why didn\'t we get to see that?" I think that\'s something we are going to do one day. Because MastersFX, we\'re professionally married...If you see another movie from us, you know its going to be MastersFX. I think we\'re going to go to one of those shows, and have all the practical pieces put onto our faces. We\'ll give people a chance to see it at another opportunity. Its really fun, and an excuse to put on prosthetics. Any chance to put on prosthetics is a chance we\'re going to take.</p><p><strong>I think it worked better for the film...</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: I\'m glad you felt that! We have changed our answer. That is what we intended!</p><p><strong>I like this idea that if we want to continue the experience of the movie, instead of a sequel, we go visit you guys wherever you may be, and we see you in your make-up.</strong></p><p><strong><a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska" rel="hc-peishlmiw9yvlp">Jen Soska</a></strong>: if we could do it like <a class="tv_show" href="http://www.movieweb.com/tv/TV9WFf9afm1Vcd" rel="hc-tv9wff9afm1vcd">Buffy the Vampire Slayer</a>, and what they did with that show, and we could bring this to TV, there are a lot of stories that we didn\'t get to say. We would absolutely go and do more. For every character, we had a vast backstory. We\'re storytellers. We\'re obsessed. We know where they are going in the future, we know where they\'ve been in the past, and what happens behind the scenes. Because the film follows Mary, and we never get to know anyone unless, and how, Mary gets to know them.</p><p><a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/american-mary" title="American Mary">American Mary</a> was released <a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movies/2013/week/2013/week/22" title="May 31st, 2013">May 31st, 2013</a> and stars <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/katharine-isabelle">Katharine Isabelle</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/antonio-cupo">Antonio Cupo</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/tristan-risk">Tristan Risk</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/david-lovgren">David Lovgren</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/paula-lindberg">Paula Lindberg</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/clay-st-thomas">Clay St. Thomas</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/john-emmet-tracy">John Emmet Tracy</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/twan-holliday">Twan Holliday</a>. The film is directed by <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/jen-soska">Jen Soska</a>, <a class="person" href="http://www.movieweb.com/person/sylvia-soska">Sylvia Soska</a>. </p>\n<div class="feedflare">\n<a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?a=PYsH64XUNDU:qUiFN48UO-U:D7DqB2pKExk"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?i=PYsH64XUNDU:qUiFN48UO-U:D7DqB2pKExk" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?a=PYsH64XUNDU:qUiFN48UO-U:qj6IDK7rITs"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?d=qj6IDK7rITs" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?a=PYsH64XUNDU:qUiFN48UO-U:I9og5sOYxJI"><img border="0" src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?d=I9og5sOYxJI" /></a> <a href="http://feeds.movieweb.com/~ff/celebrity-interviews?a=PYsH64XUNDU:qUiFN48UO-U:V_sGLiPBpWU"><img border="0"     [{'base': u'http://feeds.movieweb.com/movie-reviews-movieweb', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'<div style="float: right; margin-bottom: 10px;">\n\t<a href="http://api.tweetmeme.com/share?url=http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-adventures-of-shark-boy-lava-girl-in-3d/REPgaMWWNxK7TV&amp;service=bit.ly" target="_blank"><img align="right" height="61" src="http://api.tweetmeme.com/imagebutton.gif?url=http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-adventures-of-shark-boy-lava-girl-in-3d/REPgaMWWNxK7TV" style="border: none; margin-right: 5px;" width="51" /></a>\n\t\t<a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-adventures-of-shark-boy-lava-girl-in-3d/REPgaMWWNxK7TV&amp;src=sp" name="fb_share" style="text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" type="box_count"><img align="right" src="http://media.movieweb.com/i/img/feed/fb.jpg" style="border: none; margin-right: 5px;" /></a>\n\t</div><table><tr valign="top"><td width="132"><a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-adventures-of-shark-boy-lava-girl-in-3d/REPgaMWWNxK7TV" target="_blank"><img alt="Mr.K\'s Review of The Adventures of Shark Boy &amp; Lava Girl in 3D" border="0" src="http://wpc.556e.edgecastcdn.net/80556E/img.teasers.posters/FIf9jmjgGdh3hl_1_g.jpg" title="Mr.K\'s Review of The Adventures of Shark Boy &amp; Lava Girl in 3D" /></a></td><td>&nbsp;</td><td><p><h4><a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-adventures-of-shark-boy-lava-girl-in-3d/REPgaMWWNxK7TV" target="_blank">The Adventures of Shark Boy &amp; Lava Girl in 3D Review</a></h4></p><p>&quot;And that\'s how Robert Rodriguez lost all his dignity after this sh*t-fest of a movie.&quot; - Mr.K</p><p><img src="http://media.movieweb.com/i/img/stars/stars_white/0.5.gif" /></p><p><ul><li><a href="http://www.movieweb.com/movie/the-adventures-of-shark-boy-lava-girl-in-3d/REPgaMWWNxK7TV" target="_blank">Full Review</a></li><li><a href="http://www.movieweb.com" target="_blank">The Adventures of Shark Boy &amp; With his recent release <i>Commando</i> getting rave reviews for his action scenes it\'s no surprise.
