    {'base': u'http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/rss/news.xml', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u'Vidyut Jamwal who made an action packed debut alongside John Abraham in <i>Force</i> seems to be fast becoming the next action star of Bollywood. With his recent release <i>Commando</i> getting rave reviews for his action scenes it\'s no surprise. Now we hear that Vidyut is all set to join the league of international action legends like Jet Li and Lee Byung-Hun.<br /><br />The reason, Vidyut\'s work and his action will soon be showcased at the Fantasia International Film Festival - the ultimate large screen action extravaganza in Montreal, Canada. Says Eric S. Boisvert, one of the members on the board of the film festival, expressing his faith and belief in Vidyut, "Fantasia has always been a turning point for emerging Asian actors. Over the past 17 years Fantasia has introduced countless action stars, such as Jet Li and Lee Byung-hun, long before they exploded onto American screens. This year is no exception. We confidently guarantee you that Vidyut Jamwal will soon earn his well-deserved spot among the great names of action cinema." <br /><br />Fantasia Film Festival is the first of two international film festivals celebrating the magic of Vidyut\'s action in <i>Commando</i>. After Fantasia in Canada, <i>Commando</i> will also be showcased at the Fantastic Fest in Texas, USA which is America\'s exceptionally grand action, thriller and sci-fi film celebration.', 'language': None}

title
author
    Bollywood Hungama News Network
summary
    Vidyut Jamwal who made an action packed debut alongside John Abraham in <i>Force</i> seems to be fast becoming the next action star of Bollywood. With his recent release <i>Commando</i> getting rave reviews for his action scenes it's no surprise. Now we hear that Vidyut is all set to join the league of international action legends like Jet Li and Lee Byung-Hun.<br /><br />The reason, Vidyut's work and his action will soon be showcased at the Fantasia International Film Festival - the ultimate large screen action extravaganza in Montreal, Canada. Says Eric S. Boisvert, one of the members on the board of the film festival, expressing his faith and belief in Vidyut, "Fantasia has always been a turning point for emerging Asian actors. Over the past 17 years Fantasia has introduced countless action stars, such as Jet Li and Lee Byung-hun, long before they exploded onto American screens. This year is no exception. We confidently guarantee you that Vidyut Jamwal will soon earn his well-deserved spot among the great names of action cinema." <br /><br />Fantasia Film Festival is the first of two international film festivals celebrating the magic of Vidyut's action in <i>Commando</i>. After Fantasia in Canada, <i>Commando</i> will also be showcased at the Fantastic Fest in Texas, USA which is America's exceptionally grand action, thriller and sci-fi film celebration.

summary_detail
    {'base': u'http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/rss/movie_reviews.xml', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u"Boy meets girl. Falls in love. But family doesn't endorse their relationship. Determined, the lovers resolve to win over the displeased relatives through hard slog, willpower and integrity... Aah, haven't we visited similar themes numerous times in the past? But storytellers the world over tend to replicate stories -- with modifications and alterations, of course -- interpreting the yarn in their individualistic way.<br /><br />\n\nAfter regaling spectators with masala entertainers like WANTED and ROWDY RATHORE, Prabhu Dheva unleashes his new outing RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA. Clearly, the promos give an inkling that Prabhu dwells on the age-old formula in his third Hindi outing, a genre that's oft-repeated post MAINE PYAR KIYA [1989]. Come to think of it, not only does RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA bring back memories of MAINE PYAR KIYA, but also ANARI [1993; Venkatesh - Karisma Kapoor, with Suresh Oberoi playing the strict older brother], DILWALE DULHANIA LE JAYENGE [1995; SRK - Kajol, with Amrish Puri as the stern father] and PYAAR KIYA TO DARNA KYA [1998; Salman - Kajol, with Arbaaz enacting Kajol's authoritarian brother]. <br /><br />\n\nIn reality, RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is the remake of Prabhu Dheva's directorial debut NUVVOSTANANTE NENODDANTANA [Telugu; 2005], which was subsequently remade in other languages. The query is, why tag on the oft-repeated premise for a present-day film? But let me also add that romance is eternal and if one looks at the success ratio of this genre, the results have been fantastic, with almost every top name today having commenced his career with a love saga. <br /><br />\n\nRAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA may bear similarities with above named movies, but the drama unfurls way too differently here. Sure, there are deja\xa0 vu moments, despite the germ of thought being analogous, but Prabhu and screenplay writer Shiraz Ahmed ensure that they pack several novel and mass-friendly punches, introduce new characters, besides packaging it well enough for the entertainment-seeking spectator to lap it up. <br /><br />\n\nRam [Girish Kumar], the Australia-returned youngster, meets Sona [Shruti Haasan] at his cousin's wedding and falls in love with her. He follows her to her farm, run by her brother [Sonu Sood], who is against this match, since Ram is too affluent for them. He throws a challenge at Ram if he has to win Sona's hand in marriage...<br /><br />\n\nThe emphasis is solely and absolutely on providing entertainment in movies such as RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA and Prabhu Dheva has mastered the art since the time he donned the director's hat. The aiming-at-masses director struck the pot of gold in his first two Hindi movies and in RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA too, he ensures he ups the entertainment quotient in every frame. Of course, unlike WANTED and ROWDY RATHORE, where romance was the second-most important ingredient, the love story is the focal point of RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA, but Prabhu is not at sea tackling the genre. Furthermore, this may be atypical love story, with the spectator knowing beforehand what the wrap up would be, but the journey in the second hour specifically is pleasurable, with Prabhu and writer Shiraz Ahmed blending episodes to cater to every strata of the movie-going audience. <br /><br />\n\nRAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is not without its share of blemishes. To start with, the sequences between the lovers don't work in entirety. Note the sequence at the bath tub; it only adds to the length of the film. Besides, the narrative tends to stagnate in a few sequences, while a few episodes have been stretched for no particular reason. Cinematography [splendid work by Kiran Deohans] and the action [invigorating fights by Kaushal-Moses] are in tandem with the content of the film. <br /><br />\n\nWith Kumar Taurani [Tips] in the producer's chair, obviously, the soundtrack has to be rich. It's a given, right? And Sachin-Jigar, the talented <i>jodi</i>, doesn't disappoint either. 'Jeene Laga Hoon' is lilting and has already attained tremendous popularity, while 'Jadoo Ki Jhappi' and 'Rang Jo Lagyo' are wonderful compositions as well. Priya Panchal's lyrics compliment the melodies, while the choreography is eye-catching as well. <br /><br />\n\nObviously, RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is the launch vehicle for Girish Kumar and the actor gets the opportunity to sing, dance, fight, emote, display varied emotions... in short, the film is meant to be a showreel that shows off his acting credentials. Of course, Girish being a first-timer, there are some rough edges, but the fact is, he's photogenic and goes through the rigmarole with confidence. Whether it his introductory sequence [surfing in the sea] or breaking into a dance, whether he's exposing his chiseled physique or wearing <i>desi</i> outfits, whether he's asked to look innocent or flirtatious, Girish gets it right. <br /><br />\n\nShruti Haasan looks gorgeous and is akin to a breath of fresh breeze. She radiates innocence, but can be naughty the next minute and conveys a lot through her eyes. It would be great to see her in varied roles in times to come. Sonu Sood is exceptional. In fact, this is amongst his finest performances. The film has a gigantic supporting cast comprising of Vinod Khanna, Randhir Kapoor, Poonam Dhillon, Govind Namdev, Satish Shah, Zakir Hussain, Nasser, Sarfaraz Khan, Mushtaq Khan and Paresh Ganatra and each of them enact their respective parts with proficiency. Jacqueline Fernandez and Prabhu Dheva's song is high on energy. <br /><br />\n\nOn the whole, RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is a simplistic love story narrated competently. Besides, the chemistry between the lead actors, the gripping second hour and of course, the Hit musical score should contribute to its triumph. Recommended!", 'language': None}
published_parsed
links
    [{'href': u'http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/563935', 'type': u'text/html', 'rel': u'alternate'}]
title
author
    Taran Adarsh
summary
    Boy meets girl. Falls in love. But family doesn't endorse their relationship. Determined, the lovers resolve to win over the displeased relatives through hard slog, willpower and integrity... Aah, haven't we visited similar themes numerous times in the past? But storytellers the world over tend to replicate stories -- with modifications and alterations, of course -- interpreting the yarn in their individualistic way.<br /><br />

After regaling spectators with masala entertainers like WANTED and ROWDY RATHORE, Prabhu Dheva unleashes his new outing RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA. Clearly, the promos give an inkling that Prabhu dwells on the age-old formula in his third Hindi outing, a genre that's oft-repeated post MAINE PYAR KIYA [1989]. Come to think of it, not only does RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA bring back memories of MAINE PYAR KIYA, but also ANARI [1993; Venkatesh - Karisma Kapoor, with Suresh Oberoi playing the strict older brother], DILWALE DULHANIA LE JAYENGE [1995; SRK - Kajol, with Amrish Puri as the stern father] and PYAAR KIYA TO DARNA KYA [1998; Salman - Kajol, with Arbaaz enacting Kajol's authoritarian brother]. <br /><br />

In reality, RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is the remake of Prabhu Dheva's directorial debut NUVVOSTANANTE NENODDANTANA [Telugu; 2005], which was subsequently remade in other languages. The query is, why tag on the oft-repeated premise for a present-day film? But let me also add that romance is eternal and if one looks at the success ratio of this genre, the results have been fantastic, with almost every top name today having commenced his career with a love saga. <br /><br />

RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA may bear similarities with above named movies, but the drama unfurls way too differently here. Sure, there are deja  vu moments, despite the germ of thought being analogous, but Prabhu and screenplay writer Shiraz Ahmed ensure that they pack several novel and mass-friendly punches, introduce new characters, besides packaging it well enough for the entertainment-seeking spectator to lap it up. <br /><br />

Ram [Girish Kumar], the Australia-returned youngster, meets Sona [Shruti Haasan] at his cousin's wedding and falls in love with her. He follows her to her farm, run by her brother [Sonu Sood], who is against this match, since Ram is too affluent for them. He throws a challenge at Ram if he has to win Sona's hand in marriage...<br /><br />

The emphasis is solely and absolutely on providing entertainment in movies such as RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA and Prabhu Dheva has mastered the art since the time he donned the director's hat. The aiming-at-masses director struck the pot of gold in his first two Hindi movies and in RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA too, he ensures he ups the entertainment quotient in every frame. Of course, unlike WANTED and ROWDY RATHORE, where romance was the second-most important ingredient, the love story is the focal point of RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA, but Prabhu is not at sea tackling the genre. Furthermore, this may be atypical love story, with the spectator knowing beforehand what the wrap up would be, but the journey in the second hour specifically is pleasurable, with Prabhu and writer Shiraz Ahmed blending episodes to cater to every strata of the movie-going audience. <br /><br />

RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is not without its share of blemishes. To start with, the sequences between the lovers don't work in entirety. Note the sequence at the bath tub; it only adds to the length of the film. Besides, the narrative tends to stagnate in a few sequences, while a few episodes have been stretched for no particular reason. Cinematography [splendid work by Kiran Deohans] and the action [invigorating fights by Kaushal-Moses] are in tandem with the content of the film. <br /><br />

With Kumar Taurani [Tips] in the producer's chair, obviously, the soundtrack has to be rich. It's a given, right? And Sachin-Jigar, the talented <i>jodi</i>, doesn't disappoint either. 'Jeene Laga Hoon' is lilting and has already attained tremendous popularity, while 'Jadoo Ki Jhappi' and 'Rang Jo Lagyo' are wonderful compositions as well. Priya Panchal's lyrics compliment the melodies, while the choreography is eye-catching as well. <br /><br />

Obviously, RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is the launch vehicle for Girish Kumar and the actor gets the opportunity to sing, dance, fight, emote, display varied emotions... in short, the film is meant to be a showreel that shows off his acting credentials. Of course, Girish being a first-timer, there are some rough edges, but the fact is, he's photogenic and goes through the rigmarole with confidence. Whether it his introductory sequence [surfing in the sea] or breaking into a dance, whether he's exposing his chiseled physique or wearing <i>desi</i> outfits, whether he's asked to look innocent or flirtatious, Girish gets it right. <br /><br />

Shruti Haasan looks gorgeous and is akin to a breath of fresh breeze. She radiates innocence, but can be naughty the next minute and conveys a lot through her eyes. It would be great to see her in varied roles in times to come. Sonu Sood is exceptional. In fact, this is amongst his finest performances. The film has a gigantic supporting cast comprising of Vinod Khanna, Randhir Kapoor, Poonam Dhillon, Govind Namdev, Satish Shah, Zakir Hussain, Nasser, Sarfaraz Khan, Mushtaq Khan and Paresh Ganatra and each of them enact their respective parts with proficiency. Jacqueline Fernandez and Prabhu Dheva's song is high on energy. <br /><br />

On the whole, RAMAIYA VASTAVAIYA is a simplistic love story narrated competently. Besides, the chemistry between the lead actors, the gripping second hour and of course, the Hit musical score should contribute to its triumph. Recommended!
title_detail
link
    http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/criticreview/id/563935

With adversity comes an opportunity; a second chance that Jyotsna as a mother cannot afford to lose or fail to succeed.

summary_detail
    {'base': u'http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/rss/music_reviews.xml', 'type': u'text/html', 'value': u"<b>Music: Vipin Patwa, Sunil Bhatia & Remo Fernandes</b><br />\n<b>Lyrics: Dr. Sagar, Sanjay Mishra, Prashant Hingole, SunilBhatia & Remo Fernandes</b><br />\n<b>Music label: T-Series</b><br /><br />\n\n<b>Expectations</b><br /><br />\n\nTanuj Virwani and Neha Hinge make their debuts in this love story, which carries on the tradition of films casting two newcomers in a romance. Expectations are mixed, because we are in a different age from <i>Ek Duuje Ke Liye</i>, which was Tanuj's mom Rati Agnihotri-Virwani's debut and that of Kamal Haasan. But we would still like to have catchy, film-propping music! <br /><br />\n\n<b>Music</b><br /><br />\nThe first downer of the album is it having music directors, when one composer needed to give his all to a film about lovebirds by absorbing the story and characters. Vipin Patwa, who composes four of the six songs, and an unplugged version of one of them, has done just an adequate job without scoring the kind of songs that will boost audience interest in the film: this despite having great singers like KK, Sonu Nigam, Shreya Ghoshal and Sunidhi Chauhan. <br /><br />\n\nThe album starts with '<b><i>Tumsa nahin hai koi</i></b>' (KK-Anwesha Sarkar) and Anwesha is the same girl who sang so well in <i>Dangerous Ishhq</i> last year. The singers do a fine job, but the song sounds - a frequent malady of late - like it has wandered in from a Mukesh-Mahesh Bhatt film. The pop feel, however, gives it a shorter life as all one recalls after three hearings is the abovementioned KK refrain and not the rest of the tune! <br /><br />\n\nSonu Nigam actually gets three tracks - '<b><i>Pyar tera</i></b>', its unplugged version, and '<b><i>You are my Valentine</i></b>' (with Sunidhi Chauhan). The last mentioned just does not connect somehow despite the formidable star-duo, but '<i>Pyar hua</i>' is a sonorous, old-world tenor with placid orchestration. The unplugged version somehow seems more effective, maybe because it gives more space for Sonu to make a mark and also hum effectively - the humming is a key component of the melody, while the guitar and piano are also more relaxed and thus more evocative. <br /><br />\n\n'<b><i>Palkon pe phool</i></b>' (Shaan-Shreya) does not work despite the good singers because it is so nondescript - a jingle cannot be converted into a song, since the tune must have the substance to appeal for more than a few seconds!\nThat brings us to the title-track, written, composed and rendered by the effervescent Remo Fernandez in his trademark style. The familiar lyrics, the Goanese flavour in the song and orchestration and the steady rhythm is strangely enough more of a hark-back to well-loved R.D. Burman numbers. Remo's words are original and cute, like the line, <i>Christmas bhi tum Baisakhi bhi tum</i>, which gives the film's game away - clearly the hero is a Christian and the heroine a <i>Punjab di kudi</i>! <br /><br />\n\nAnd so we comes to the best track on the album in terms of recall value - Sunil Bhatia's '<b><i>Chalo chalte hain Mexico</i></b>' (Shaan) with its harmonious sound and old-world blend of Indian and Western grooves. Shaan gets to sing in both Hindi and English Shaan in this acoustics-based soft number, with rich piano notes and a general jazz-meets-teenybopper-meets Shankar-Jaikishan feel. Weirdly, the female singer is not credited in the inlay. However, the song isn't one of those strong numbers that will boost the numbers for either album or film. <br /><br />\n\nAs for the '<b><i>Luv U Soniyo Mashup</i></b>' - like the majority of them, it is just an intentional clutter and eminently forgettable. <br /><br />\n\n<b>Overall</b><br /><br />\nWe expected better music in a teenage love story focused on just one hero and heroine, both of whom are making their debuts. Maybe <i>Bobby, Ek Duuje Ke Liye, Betaab</i> and <i>Hero</i> are too much to expect nowadays, but the level could have more towards at least a <i>Saawariya</i>! <br /><br />\n\n<b>Our Picks</b><br /><br />\n\n<i>Chalo chalte hai Mexico, Luv U Soniyo</i>", 'language': None}
published_parsed
links
    [{'href': u'http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/musiccriticreview/id/542615', 'type': u'text/html', 'rel': u'alternate'}]
title
author
    Rajiv Vijayakar
summary
    <b>Music: Vipin Patwa, Sunil Bhatia & Remo Fernandes</b><br />
<b>Lyrics: Dr. Sagar, Sanjay Mishra, Prashant Hingole, SunilBhatia & Remo Fernandes</b><br />
<b>Music label: T-Series</b><br /><br />

<b>Expectations</b><br /><br />

Tanuj Virwani and Neha Hinge make their debuts in this love story, which carries on the tradition of films casting two newcomers in a romance. Expectations are mixed, because we are in a different age from <i>Ek Duuje Ke Liye</i>, which was Tanuj's mom Rati Agnihotri-Virwani's debut and that of Kamal Haasan. But we would still like to have catchy, film-propping music! <br /><br />

<b>Music</b><br /><br />
The first downer of the album is it having music directors, when one composer needed to give his all to a film about lovebirds by absorbing the story and characters. Vipin Patwa, who composes four of the six songs, and an unplugged version of one of them, has done just an adequate job without scoring the kind of songs that will boost audience interest in the film: this despite having great singers like KK, Sonu Nigam, Shreya Ghoshal and Sunidhi Chauhan. <br /><br />

The album starts with '<b><i>Tumsa nahin hai koi</i></b>' (KK-Anwesha Sarkar) and Anwesha is the same girl who sang so well in <i>Dangerous Ishhq</i> last year. The singers do a fine job, but the song sounds - a frequent malady of late - like it has wandered in from a Mukesh-Mahesh Bhatt film. The pop feel, however, gives it a shorter life as all one recalls after three hearings is the abovementioned KK refrain and not the rest of the tune! <br /><br />

Sonu Nigam actually gets three tracks - '<b><i>Pyar tera</i></b>', its unplugged version, and '<b><i>You are my Valentine</i></b>' (with Sunidhi Chauhan). The last mentioned just does not connect somehow despite the formidable star-duo, but '<i>Pyar hua</i>' is a sonorous, old-world tenor with placid orchestration. The unplugged version somehow seems more effective, maybe because it gives more space for Sonu to make a mark and also hum effectively - the humming is a key component of the melody, while the guitar and piano are also more relaxed and thus more evocative. <br /><br />

'<b><i>Palkon pe phool</i></b>' (Shaan-Shreya) does not work despite the good singers because it is so nondescript - a jingle cannot be converted into a song, since the tune must have the substance to appeal for more than a few seconds!
That brings us to the title-track, written, composed and rendered by the effervescent Remo Fernandez in his trademark style. The familiar lyrics, the Goanese flavour in the song and orchestration and the steady rhythm is strangely enough more of a hark-back to well-loved R.D. Burman numbers. Remo's words are original and cute, like the line, <i>Christmas bhi tum Baisakhi bhi tum</i>, which gives the film's game away - clearly the hero is a Christian and the heroine a <i>Punjab di kudi</i>! <br /><br />

And so we comes to the best track on the album in terms of recall value - Sunil Bhatia's '<b><i>Chalo chalte hain Mexico</i></b>' (Shaan) with its harmonious sound and old-world blend of Indian and Western grooves. Shaan gets to sing in both Hindi and English Shaan in this acoustics-based soft number, with rich piano notes and a general jazz-meets-teenybopper-meets Shankar-Jaikishan feel. Weirdly, the female singer is not credited in the inlay. However, the song isn't one of those strong numbers that will boost the numbers for either album or film. <br /><br />

As for the '<b><i>Luv U Soniyo Mashup</i></b>' - like the majority of them, it is just an intentional clutter and eminently forgettable. <br /><br />

<b>Overall</b><br /><br />
We expected better music in a teenage love story focused on just one hero and heroine, both of whom are making their debuts. Maybe <i>Bobby, Ek Duuje Ke Liye, Betaab</i> and <i>Hero</i> are too much to expect nowadays, but the level could have more towards at least a <i>Saawariya</i>! <br /><br />

<b>Our Picks</b><br /><br />

<i>Chalo chalte hai Mexico, Luv U Soniyo</i>
title_detail
link
    http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/musiccriticreview/id/542615

    <p>Michelle Nunn just raised the stakes in Georgia’s Republican primary for U.S. Senate.</p> <p>In <a summary
    The newspapers are full of stories about how poverty in India has reduced drastically during the first 7 years of UPA rule. Annual declines have been 2.18% per year compared to just 0.74% during the previous 11 years. In my mind, there is nothing surprising about this data. The UPA government&rsquo;s constant thrust has been on reviving the rural economy and providing some sort of a decent living to the people there. People like us in urban areas may complain about the government&rsquo;s..

tags
    [{'term': u'Maryland Department of Agriculture', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}]
summary
    <p>Of pests and predators the Washington region has no shortage, and it appears that a new one has arrived on the scene: the kudzu bug.</p> <p>University of Maryland researchers have found the new arrival this summer in five counties in the region, including Prince George’s, Charles and Anne Arundel, the university said. The research team under entomology professor William Lamp has also detected it in Calvert and St. Mary’s counties, the university said. It has also been reported in several Virginia counties, including Culpeper, Frederick and Warren.</p> <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/kudzu-bug-spreads-to-maryland/2013/07/23/3409980e-f3fd-11e2-a2f1-a7acf9bd5d3a_story.html?wprss=rss_local">Read full article &#62;&#62;</a><img border="0" summary
    <p>Tires were slashed on at least 15 Toyota Prius cars in Arlington County sometime Sunday night or early Monday, police said. </p> <p>Police said the vandalism was discovered Monday morning. They said the incidents had occurred across the county, but it appeared that the Cherrydale and Waverly Hills neighborhoods of North Arlington were the sites of the greatest number of the incidents. The Prius is a popular hybrid vehicle. </p> <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/at-least-15-toyota-priuses-have-their-tires-slashed-in-arlington/2013/07/23/b29a7886-f408-11e2-a2f1-a7acf9bd5d3a_story.html?wprss=rss_crime">Read full article summary

McDonnell announced Tuesday that he repaid more than <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/va-politics/mcdonnells-corporation-wife-benefited-from-120000-more-from-donor-sources-say/2013/07/09/79b29880-e5b4-11e2-aef3-339619eab080_story.html?hpid=z1"     <p>RICHMOND — Gov. Robert F. McDonnell announced Tuesday that he repaid more than <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/va-politics/mcdonnells-corporation-wife-benefited-from-120000-more-from-donor-sources-say/2013/07/09/79b29880-e5b4-11e2-aef3-339619eab080_story.html?hpid=z1" summary
    <p>RICHMOND — Gov. Robert F. McDonnell announced Tuesday that he repaid more than <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/va-politics/mcdonnells-corporation-wife-benefited-from-120000-more-from-donor-sources-say/2013/07/09/79b29880-e5b4-11e2-aef3-339619eab080_story.html?hpid=z1" target="_blank">$120,000 in loans</a> to a businessman whose nutritional supplement he and his wife promoted, and he apologized for the first time for a gifts scandal that has consumed his final year in office.</p> <a
